[4] Bat, human exposure - Texas
Date: Thu 2 Sep 2010
Source: KENS 5.com [edited]
<http://www.kens5.com/news/Rabid-bat-discovered-at-an-East-Central-middle-school-102119914.html>


An East Central middle-schooler is being treated for rabies after
doctors say he came into contact with a rabid bat. Stevie Gonzales, a
spokesperson for East Central School District says the 7th grader at
Legacy Middle School [in San Antonio], found the bat and brought it
inside the school. Gonzales says once a teacher discovered it, the
bat was taken away and given to animal control where the bat was later tested.

According to Dr Fernando Guerra with Metro Health, the bat tested
positive for rabies. "As a result, the student had to receive
vaccinations and treatments to limit the exposure," Said Guerra.

"If a bite from a rabid animal goes untreated and an infection
develops" Dr Guerra said, "it is almost always fatal." Dr Guerra
warns that anyone exposed to a rabid animal must go to the emergency
room immediately. Guerra says even if the person is not bitten, there
is a chance he or she may still be infected.

Meanwhile Gonzales says the school district has notified all teachers
and parents. "We ask parents to please talk to your children, please
ask them if they have been in contact with a bat, and we have talked
to Legacy Middle School. They are continuing to monitor the school to
make sure there are no more sightings of bats," Said Gonzales.

Since rabies is not [usually] contagious [between humans], Gonzales
says the student has returned to school but is still undergoing treatments.

[Byline: Sarah Forgany]

