[5] Ovine, skunk, human exposure - Nebraska
Date: Fri 3 Sep 2010
Source: The Wauneta Breeze, The Imperial Republican report [edited]
<http://www.waunetanebraska.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2173:rabid-sheep-causes-stir-at-the-fair&catid=25:local-news&Itemid=34>


[Imperial] Fair livestock exhibitors and superintendents got a little
unnerved early last week [week of 23 Aug 2010] when it was learned a
sheep that was intended to be shown at the fair had contracted
rabies. While the rabid sheep had been put down before the fair, 4
pen-mates had already been brought into the livestock barns.

As soon as the owners found out the market lamb tested positive for
rabies, the other 4 sheep were removed from the grounds. Tests later
showed that all 4 animals brought to the fair tested negative for rabies.

The sheep were 4-H [youth organization administered by the USDA] and
FFA [youth organization that promotes and supports agricultural
education] projects of the 3 older children of a couple that are
residents of rural Imperial. The daughter noticed the affected lamb
wasn't eating well during the week before the fair. They tried some
treatments but the animal didn't respond. The animal started becoming
aggressive in the pen and with the other pen-mates. This behavior,
along with the eating behavior of the sheep, prompted them to call
local veterinarian, Dr Dave Johnsen Sunday night, 15 Aug 2010.

Together, they determined there was something wrong with the animal
and decided not to take it to the fair. The sheep was put down that
evening and Johnsen decided to send the sheep's brain to the lab at
Kansas State, where rabies testing is done. Surprisingly, the test
came back positive on Tue 17 Aug 2010.

Johnsen realized something wasn't right with the sheep but said he
never really suspected rabies. He could only speculate on how the
sheep contracted rabies. He said the residents told him they had shot
a strange acting skunk about 4 to 6 weeks prior. Dr Johnsen said it's
possible the skunk could have bitten the sheep but the real cause
will likely never be known.

After the positive test, he notified the resident, who had already
checked in the 4 other pen-mates at the fair that morning. The sheep
were removed from the grounds Tuesday afternoon [17 Aug 2010]. Dr
Johnsen kept the sheep at his clinic, before putting them down for
further testing. Johnsen said the brains of the 4 other sheep tested
normal with no rabies conditions present.

The resident said they would have never brought their other sheep to
the fair had they known the one was positive for rabies. Dr Johnsen
said rabies doesn't pass from animal to animal [unless they bite or
scratch] so the likelihood the other 4 animals were infected was very slim.

While the information the other 4 tested negative proved to be good
news, it didn't offset the fact that all 7 members of the family had
to have rabies shots.

The owner said she panicked when she first heard the lamb had rabies.
There wasn't a sufficient supply of rabies vaccine in area hospitals
so they drove to Denver [Colorado], where an ample supply existed.
While it was ample for the family, she said their shots took half of
the rabies vaccine supply in Denver.

A young neighbor who had played with the sheep also received the
vaccine series.

This is a wake-up call to the 4-H council and the fair board as to
what procedures are in place if an animal is found to be infected
and/or contagious. While there was some immediate panic about the
situation, Dr Johnsen said the proper precautions were taken by
removing the animals from the grounds and having them tested.

[Byline: Russ Pankonin]

